{"title":"Multiscale Sensor Fusion and Continuous Control with Neural CDEs","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Robotic policies must fuse asynchronous, multi-frequency sensory streams (e.g., sparse images with high-rate proprioception/forces) and act nearly in continuous time. Common approaches batch observations into fixed windows or use open-loop primitives, failing to capture fast in-between dynamics and temporal structure.","method":"Introduce InFuser, a hybrid continuous-time policy that treats control as the solution of a Neural Controlled Differential Equation. The model conditions on an image embedding and is driven by the higher-frequency sensor stream to evolve a continuous-time multisensory latent state, from which actions are decoded at any intermediate time. The initial action uses only currently available measurements, while subsequent actions integrate new high-rate observations via the CDE. Training uses adjoint-based backpropagation and behavior cloning over control functions. The architecture includes passing high-frequency measurements as a subvector of the latent and stacking an identity block in the CDE vector field, and it generalizes ODE/RNN/DMP parameterizations."},{"problem":"Continuous-time CDE policies must be causal for real-time deployment, but natural cubic spline interpolation induces non-causal dependencies on future data.","method":"Propose a discretely-online CDE evolution: output control at a fixed high rate and evolve the CDE over successive short intervals, where at each step the cubic spline is fit only to measurements within the current interval. This preserves causality at the control frequency while retaining smooth integration of high-rate signals between sparse images. For truly continuous-time control, a zero-order-hold interpolant can be used. This strategy enables practical, real-time deployment of CDE-driven policies without violating causality."},{"problem":"Existing evaluations often assume fixed image rates and no sensor loss, obscuring the robustness benefits of temporally expressive models on dynamic tasks.","method":"Introduce Throttled-BC (varying the number of control steps between images) and Dropped-BC (random image drops) evaluation protocols, fine-tuning from nominal models. Empirically demonstrate that InFuser achieves higher success (r_max) and efficiency (r_Σ) than SB, MA-SB, and DMP-based NDP as image rates are throttled and under drop conditions on dynamic Ball-in-Cup and its harder variant (force-torque only), while remaining competitive on quasi-static cloth covering. The gains stem from InFuser’s stateful latent dynamics, which support nontrivial latent prediction and conversion from force-torque feedback to proprioceptive-level information."}]}
